Name: Abdomen
Description: The part of the body of a vertebrate containing the digestive organs; the belly

Name: Adrenal
Description: Relating to or denoting a pair of ductless glands situated above the kidneys.

Name: Arm
Description: Each of the forelimbs of an animal.

Name: Bark
Description: Bark is the outermost layers of stems and roots of woody plants. Plants with bark include trees, woody vines, and shrubs. Bark refers to all the tissues outside the vascular cambium and is a nontechnical term. It overlays the wood and consists of the inner bark and the outer bark.

Name: Bile
Description: A greenish-brown alkaline fluid that aids digestion and is secreted by the liver and stored in the gallbladder.

Name: Blood
Description: The red liquid that circulates in the arteries and veins of humans and other vertebrate animals, carrying oxygen to and carbon dioxide from the tissues of the body.

Name: Blood Plasma
Description: A yellowish liquid component of blood that holds the blood cells in whole blood in suspension.

Name: Body
Description: The physical structure of a person or an animal, including the bones, flesh, and organs.

Name: Body Wall
Description: The external surface of an animal body that encloses the body cavity.

Name: Bone Tissue
Description: Bone tissue (osseous tissue) is a hard tissue, a type of dense connective tissue. It has a honeycomb-like matrix internally, which helps to give the bone rigidity. Bone tissue is made up of different types of bone cells. Osteoblasts and osteocytes are involved in the formation and mineralization of bone; osteoclasts are involved in the resorption of bone tissue.

Name: Bone, Acellular
Description: Not consisting of, divided into, or containing cells.(especially of protozoa) consisting of one cell only. Acellular bone is true bone, differing from all other vertebrate bone in the total lack of enclosed osteocytes

Name: Bone, Cellular
Description: There are two main types of bone cells: osteocytes and osteoblasts. (i.e., bone containing osteocytes that are regularly spaced throughout the bone matrix). Osteoblasts is a cell that secretes the matrix (composed of protein and minerals) for bone formation.

Name: Bone, Marrow
Description: A semi-solid tissue which may be found within the spongy or cancellous portions of bones.

Name: Brain
Description: An organ of soft nervous tissue contained in the skull of vertebrates, functioning as the coordinating center of sensation and nervous activity.

Name: Carapace
Description: The hard upper shell of a turtle, crustacean, or arachnid.

Name: Connective Tissue
Description: Tissue that connects, supports, binds, or separates other tissues or organs, typically having relatively few cells embedded in an amorphous matrix, often with collagen or other fibers, and including cartilaginous, fatty, and elastic tissues.

Name: Digestive Gland
Description: a glandular organ of digestion present in crustaceans, mollusks, and certain other invertebrates.

Name: Ear
Description: The organ of hearing and balance in humans and other vertebrates.

Name: Egg/Ovum
Description: The female reproductive cell in animals and plants.

Name: Eye
Description: Each of a pair of globular organs in the head through which people and vertebrate animals see.

Name: Fat/Adipose Tissue
Description: A natural oily or greasy substance occurring in animal bodies, especially when deposited as a layer under the skin or around certain organs.

Name: Feather
Description: Any of the flat appendages growing from a bird's skin and forming its plumage, consisting of a partly hollow horny shaft fringed with vanes of barbs.

Name: Feces
Description: Waste matter discharged from the bowels after food has been digested.

Name: Fin
Description: A flattened appendage on various parts of the body of many aquaticvertebrates and some invertebrates

Name: Fish Scales
Description: A small rigid plate that grows out of the skin of a fish.

Name: Flower
Description: The seed-bearing part of a plant, consisting of reproductive organs (stamens and carpels) that are typically surrounded by a brightly colored corolla (petals) and a green calyx (sepals).

Name: Foot
Description: The lower extremity of the leg below the ankle, on which an animal stands or walks.

Name: Fore Gut
Description: The anterior part of the gut, toward the mouth.

Name: Fruit
Description: The sweet and fleshy product of a tree or other plant that contains seed and can be eaten as food.

Name: Gall Bladder
Description: The small sac-shaped organ beneath the liver, in which bile is storedafter secretion by the liver and before release into the intestine.

Name: Gill Rakers
Description: Bony or cartilaginous outgrowths that project from the branchial arch.

Name: Gills
Description: The respiratory organ of fishes and some amphibians, by which oxygen is extracted from water flowing over surfaces within or attached to the walls of the pharynx.

Name: Gonads
Description: An organ that produces gametes; a testis or ovary.

Name: Gut
Description: The stomach or belly.

Name: Head
Description: The front or upper part of the body of an animal, typically separated from the rest of the body by a neck, and containing the brain, mouth, and sense organs.

Name: Heart
Description: A hollow muscular organ that pumps the blood through the circulatory system by rhythmic contraction and dilation.

Name: Hepatopancreas
Description: A glandular organ of digestion present in crustaceans, mollusks, and certain other invertebrates.

Name: Hind Gut
Description: The posterior part of the gut, toward the anus.

Name: Intestine
Description: The lower part of the digestive system from the end of the stomach to the anus.

Name: Kidney
Description: Each of a pair of organs in the abdominal cavity of mammals, birds, and reptiles, excreting urine.

Name: Leaf
Description: A flattened structure of a higher plant, typically green and bladelike, that is attached to a stem directly or via a stalk. Leaves are the main organs of photosynthesis and transpiration.

Name: Liver
Description: A large lobed glandular organ in the abdomen of vertebrates, involved in many metabolic processes.

Name: Lung
Description: Each of the pair of organs situated within the rib cage, consisting of elastic sacs with branching passages into which air is drawn, so that oxygen can pass into the blood and carbon dioxide be removed.

Name: Milk
Description: An opaque white fluid rich in fat and protein, secreted by female mammals for the nourishment of their young.

Name: Muscle, Somatic
Description: includes most skeletal muscle.

Name: Muscle, Visceral
Description: Visceral muscle tissue, or smooth muscle, is tissue associated with the internal organs of the body, especially those in the abdominal cavity. There are three types of muscle in the body: skeletal, smooth, and cardiac. As with any muscle, the smooth, involuntary muscles of the visceral muscle tissue (which lines the blood vessels, stomach, digestive tract, and other internal organs) are composed of bundles of specialized cells capable of contraction and relaxation to create movement.

Name: Muscle/Muscle Tissue
Description: A band or bundle of fibrous tissue in an animal body that has the ability to contract, producing movement in or maintaining the position of parts of the body.

Name: Nerve Tissue
Description: A whitish fiber or bundle of fibers that transmits impulses of sensation to the brain or spinal cord, and impulses from these to the muscles and organs.

Name: Offal
Description: The entrails and internal organs of an animal used as food.

Name: Otoliths
Description: Each of three small oval calcareous bodies in the inner ear of vertebrates, involved in sensing gravity and movement.

Name: Ovary
Description: A female reproductive organ in which ova or eggs are produced.

Name: Pancreas
Description: A large gland behind the stomach which secretes digestive enzymes into the duodenum.

Name: Pistil
Description: The female organs of a flower, comprising the stigma, style, and ovary.

Name: Root
Description: The part of a plant which attaches it to the ground or to a support, typically underground, conveying water and nourishment to the rest of the plant via numerous branches and fibers.

Name: Root/Tuber
Description: A much thickened underground part of a stem or rhizome.

Name: Saliva
Description: Watery liquid secreted into the mouth by glands, providing lubrication for chewing and swallowing, and aiding digestion.

Name: Seed
Description: A flowering plant's unit of reproduction, capable of developing into another such plant.

Name: Skeleton
Description: An internal or external framework of bone, cartilage, or other rigid material supporting or containing the body of an animal.

Name: Skin
Description: The thin layer of tissue forming the natural outer covering of the body of an animal.

Name: Spleen
Description: An abdominal organ involved in the production and removal of blood cells in most vertebrates and forming part of the immune system.

Name: Stamen
Description: The male fertilizing organ of a flower, typically consisting of a pollen-containing anther and a filament.

Name: Stem
Description: The main body or stalk of a plant or shrub, typically rising above the ground.

Name: Stomach
Description: The internal organ in which the major part of the digestion of food occurs.

Name: Tentacles
Description: A slender, flexible limb or appendage in an animal, especially around the mouth of an invertebrate, used for grasping or moving about, or bearing sense organs.

Name: Testes
Description: An organ which produces spermatozoa (male reproductive cells).

Name: Thymus
Description: A lymphoid organ situated in the neck of vertebrates that produces T cells for the immune system.

Name: Tissue+Mantle Cavity Fluid
Description: The mantle cavity is a central feature of molluscan biology. This cavity is formed by the mantle skirt, a double fold of mantle which encloses a water space. This space contains the mollusc's gills, anus, and organs for taste, excretion and reproductive organs.

Name: Tissue, Unspecified
Description: Any of the distinct types of material of which animals or plants are made, consisting of specialized cells and their products.

Name: Urine
Description: A watery, typically yellowish fluid stored in the bladder and discharged through the urethra.

Name: Whole Fish, No Eggs/Muscle/Residual Ovaries
Description: Residual fish after removal of eggs, muscle and residual ovaries

Name: Whole Fish, No Stomach Contents
Description: Fish with stomach contents removed

Name: Whole Organism
Description: An organism may be defined as an assembly of molecules functioning as a more or less stable whole that exhibits the properties of life. Any individual entity that embodies the properties of life such as "any living structure, such as a plant, animal, fungus or bacterium, capable of growth and reproduction"

Name: Whole, No Exoskeleton/Shell
Description: Whole organism, no exoskeleton or shell

Name: Whole, NoStomachContents/Gills
Description: Whole organism, no stomach contents or gills

Name: Wing
Description: A modified forelimb that bears large feathers and is used for flying.

Name: Wood
Description: The hard fibrous material that forms the main substance of the trunk or branches of a tree or shrub.
